tity, and narrative. The result is a compelling portrait of this frequently misunderstood religious movement. Neo-paganism began emerging as a new religious movement in the late 1960s. In addition to bringing together followers for self-exploration and participation in group rituals, festivals might offer workshops on subjects such as astrology, tarot, mythology, herbal lore, and African drumming. But while they provide a sense of community for followers, Neo-Pagan festivals often provoke criticism from a variety of sources—among them conservative Christians, Native Americans, New Age spokespersons, and media representatives covering stories of rumored "Satanism" or "witchcraft."Earthly Bodies, Magical Selves explores larger issues in the United States regarding the postmodern self, utopian communities, cultural improvisation, and contemporary spirituality. Pike's accessible writing style and her nonsensationalistic approach do much to demystify neo-paganism and its followers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFestivalsxUnited States. 0aFestivalszUnited States. 0aNeopaganismxRituals. 0aNeopaganismxUnited States. 0aNeopaganismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aafrican american.  aancient world.  achristianity.  acommunity.  acostume.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  aculture.  aerotic.  aeroticism.  afestivals.  afolklore.  agender studies.  amagic.  amagical.  amyths.  aneopagan.  apagan festivals.  apagan gods.  apagan history.  apagan religion.  apaganism.  apagans.  areligion.  areligious studies.  asatanism.  asocial history.  asocial studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092380540uhttps